                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Necros are given pets, heals, lifetaps, dots, nukes, (snare/root) like wizzies, mez, charm, slow. All these things. It's FAIR to have penaltys on spells for us, we're too UBER! We NEED To have the mana cost unfair, because it's the only way we can have a balanced class w/ others.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />A laundry list of all our abilities sure makes me feel balanced. <img src="images/crazy.gif" border="0" alt="" title="" align="middle" />  Let's see, by the same argument, I can say that because wizards get ports, evacs, nukes, rains, snare/root, aggro-reducers, lures, gather mana, and sword pets they are too UBER! <br /><br />...<br /><br />Okay that was a bit harsh, but my point is that versatility is not simply created through a laundry list of limited abilities.  Our heals aren't worth crap at the higher ends and neither are our fears, mezzes, or charms.  We get slow - but only undead slow, and while we get "lifetaps, dots, and nukes" those three things are just aspects of the same facet: DPS, which is exactly what necromancers are at the higher end of the game.<br /><br />Unless we see some significant upgrade to our utility spells in LDoN (and it looks like we're not going to), it is folly to argue that necromancers (and consequently mages) are anything but a primary damage-dealer like the wizard.  The difference lies primarily in the methods through which we do damage.  Wizards deal damage through one method and that is nuking.  We do damage through three methods (pets, dots, and nukes).  Ultimately, our three methods of dealing damage should add up to the wizards' one method in most situations (and it currently does), but it does not mean that because we have three avenues of dealing damage we are somehow stronger or more versatile.  Wizards may seem singular, but they have ways to deal great damage to any mob - even the lifetap-resisting hyper-resistant mobs we can't touch except with pets - and that is a versatility in and of itself.<br /><br />I would delve further into the matter of balance in terms of these fast-acting new DoTs, but because it seems that they've not yet been finalized I'll give them more time before I render judgment.  <br /><br />But I did want to respond to blanket statements concerning necro versatility.  Now that our ability to solo in the new zones have been taken away, it's more urgent than ever that we realize the limits of our utility abilities and our increasingly one-sided role as damage dealer.<br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="bottom"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Etadanik the Redeemed</span></font></td>
                    </tr>
